      <body><pb n="182"/>
         <head>To <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1420.xml"/>George Merryweather</persName>
            <note place="foot" n="1"><persName><ref target="/persons/pers1420.xml"/>George Merryweather</persName>
            was a merchant in <placeName>Yarm on Tees</placeName>, who became in the late <date>1740s</date><!--range, to be changed later-->
            an active promoter and generous patron of Methodism, especially within the extensive <placeName>Yarm</placeName>
            circuit</note></head>
         <opener><placeName>Brentford</placeName><lb/><date when="1760-01-24">January 24, 1760</date><lb/><lb/>
            <salute>My Dear Brother,</salute>
         </opener>
         <p>I received yours with the bill a day or two ago. I wish you would
            everywhere recommend two books in particular—<hi rend="italic">The Christian
            Pattern</hi> and the <hi rend="italic">Primitive Physick</hi>
            <note place="foot" n="2">I.e., <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>
            &apos;s abridged version of Thomas à<!--special character, accented a--> Kempis&apos;s 
            <hi rend="italic">The Imitation of Christ</hi> (Bibliography, No. 45) and his collection of 
            medical advice (Bibliography, No. 138 and Vol. 32 in this edn.).</note>. 
            Tis a great pity that any Methodist should be without them.</p>
         <p>I wonder brother <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1391.xml"/>Mather</persName>
            <note place="foot" n="3"><persName><ref target="/persons/pers1391.xml"/>Alexander Mather</persName> (<date from="1733" to="1800">1733–1800</date>) 
            was converted under <persName><ref target="persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s preaching in <placeName>London</placeName>in
            <date when="1754">1754</date> and became an itinerant in <date when="1757">1757</date>. 
            For more detail, see <hi rend="italic">EMP</hi>, 2:158–239; Atmore, <hi rend="italic">Memorial</hi>, 256–66; and 21:309, n. 78 in this edn.</note> 
            does not write to me. He should not forget his friends. I hope the gentleman with whom I breakfasted at
            <placeName>Yarm</placeName><note place="foot" n="4">Perhaps 
            <persName>Mr.Waldy</persName>, a landed proprietor in <placeName>Yarm</placeName> to 
            whom <persName><ref target="persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> 
            referred in a letter to <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1420.xml"/>Merryweather</persName> of 
            <date when="1767-12-28">Dec. 28, 1767</date>.</note> 
            has not forsaken you. <index indexName="biblical">
            <term cRef="Matt19:24">Even the rich <hi rend="italic">may</hi> enter into the kingdom</term></index>,
            <index indexName="biblical"><term cRef="Matt19:26">for with God all things are possible.</term></index></p>
            <!--Biblical allusion to Matthew chapter 19 verse 24 and 26 missing. Added here -->
         <p>See that you stir up the gift of God that is in you.
            <note place="foot" n="5">See <index indexName="biblical">
            <term cRef="2Tim1:6">2 Tim. 1:6</term></index>.</note> 
            What is our Lord&apos;s word to <hi rend="italic">you</hi>? &apos;<index indexName="biblical">
               <term cRef="Matt8:22">Let the dead bury their dead; but follow thou
                  me!</term></index>&apos;<note place="foot" n="6"><index indexName="biblical">
            <term cRef="Matt8:22">Matt. 8:22</term></index>.</note></p>
         <closer>I am,<lb/>
            <signed>Your affectionate brother,<lb/><persName>John Wesley</persName></signed></closer>
      </body>
   </text>
